Democracy without people's connection.
Something has befallen democracy in the sense that the government is elected by the people, and that has happened everywhere in the world.
In some way, people have lost faith in elections.
Voter turnout is declining in many countries; in the case of the European Parliament elections, the turnout was so ridiculously low that the legitimacy of the election result is questionable.
Aside from voter turnout, we have become accustomed to accepting parties or candidates who receive 25% of the cast votes as "winners".
From Holland to Finland, and from Argentina to Japan, majorities are formed on the basis of minorities.
Even the apparent exceptions do not prove the opposite.
Few American Presidents have been elected by more than 10% of eligible voters. In fact, half of the eligible voters in the US have not even registered to participate in the election; of those who have registered, half do not vote; and of those who do vote, less than half vote for the winner.
Even Tony Blair's "watershed" majority in the British House of Commons stands on shaky ground: the Labour Party received only just over 40% of the votes in the last election in 2002, and that at a turnout of 60%.
According to this, even Blair's party received support from only 24% of the total electorate.
In most countries, the elections look very different from what they were like twenty or even fifty years ago.
What has happened?
One possible answer is that voters have lost trust in the political parties.
Democracy functions in most countries through the mediation of organizations that put up candidates who enter for specific packages of political possibilities, for a "manifesto" or an "election programme."
For a number of reasons, this tried-and-tested practice no longer works.
Ideological party programs have lost their strength; voters no longer accept the packages tied up by the parties, they want to pick and choose for themselves.
In addition, political parties have become machines composed of tightly organized teams of insiders.
The parties have become even more cliquey with the loss of their specific ideological orientation.
It is more important to them to belong than to share specific convictions.
Such developments have alienated the parties from the voter.
Because most people do not want to belong to any particular party, only a minority is playing the party game.
That way, public distrust of political parties grows, not least because it is, like in professional sports, expensive to play along.
When the costs are borne by the taxpayer, they are resented.
Without the financial support of the state, parties would have to obtain funds through channels that are often questionable, if not even illegal.
Many of the major political scandals of the last decades began with the financing of parties and their candidates.
Other indicators, such as the clear decline in memberships, confirm that the parties have become unpopular.
Parties are indispensable for a democratic election process.
The result is an obvious disconnect between the visible political actors and the electorate.
Because parties are active in parliaments, the effects of this disconnect impact one of the most crucial institutions of democracy.
People no longer believe that parliaments represent them and thereby possess the necessary legitimacy to make decisions on their behalf.
At this point, a second, quite independent development comes into play.
People are today more impatient than ever before.
As consumers, they are accustomed to immediate satisfaction.
But as voters, they have to wait before they can feel the effects of the election results that they cast at the ballot box.
They often never see the desired outcomes.
Democracy needs time not only for elections, but also for discussions and thoughtful weighing of options.
As consumers, they are accustomed to immediate satisfaction, the consumer as voter will not accept this, however, and therefore turns away.
There are alternatives. However, each has its own problems as a democratic solution.
Direct Action through demonstrations became a regular and often effective event.
For less mobile people, it could be replaced by the possibility of being able to express their opinion electronically; this ranges from internet chat rooms to electronic messages to political leaders.
Then there are non-governmental organizations. They often have undemocratic internal structures, yet still seem to be more closely connected to citizens.
Furthermore, there is, of course, the option to opt out entirely and leave politics to the experts, in order to focus on other aspects of life.
This development fosters the greatest risks, as it promotes creeping authoritarianism, a hallmark of our times.
But other signs of the disconnect between politics and citizens also contribute to a rather insecure situation, as no one can say anymore how representative the prevailing views are.
Some want to break through the knot by more direct democracy.
However, establishing a lasting connection between leaders and the led cannot be achieved by reducing public discussion to simple ballot options.
It would be even more to justify holding fast to the classical institutions of parliamentary democracy and trying to link them closer to the citizenry again.
At least, unpopular parties and declining voter turnout could prove to be a temporary phenomenon.
New parties could emerge and infuse elections and representative governments with more vitality.
However, this may not be enough to restore the overall legitimacy that elected governments have lost.
Therefore, the primary concern of all those who hold the constitution of freedom dear must be to rethink democracy and its institutions.
